Sarcoidosis: Sarcoidosis can cause lymphopenia, mononeuritis multiplex, and nonscarring alopecia. Nasal ulcers are less common, but can occur.
Lyme disease: Lyme disease can cause lymphopenia, mononeuritis multiplex, and nonscarring alopecia. Nasal ulcers are not typically associated with Lyme disease.
Sjögrens syndrome: Sjögrens syndrome can cause lymphopenia, mononeuritis multiplex, and nonscarring alopecia. Nasal ulcers are not typically associated with Sjögrens syndrome.
Systemic lupus erythematosus (SLE): SLE can cause lymphopenia, mononeuritis multiplex, and nonscarring alopecia. Nasal ulcers are also a possible symptom of SLE.
Wegeners granulomatosis: Wegeners granulomatosis can cause lymphopenia, mononeuritis multiplex, and nasal ulcers. Nonscarring alopecia is not typically associated with Wegeners granulomatosis.
Behçets disease: Behçets disease can cause lymphopenia, mononeuritis multiplex, and oral ulcers. Nasal ulcers are not typically associated with Behçets disease.
Churg-Strauss syndrome: Churg-Strauss syndrome can cause lymphopenia, mononeuritis multiplex, and nasal ulcers. Nonscarring alopecia is not typically associated with Churg-Strauss syndrome.
Polyarteritis nodosa: Polyarteritis nodosa can cause lymphopenia, mononeuritis multiplex, and nasal ulcers. Nonscarring alopecia is not typically associated with polyarteritis nodosa.
Microscopic polyangiitis: Microscopic polyangiitis can cause lymphopenia, mononeuritis multiplex, and nasal ulcers. Nonscarring alopecia is not typically associated with microscopic polyangiitis.
Granulomatosis with polyangiitis (GPA): GPA can cause lymphopenia, mononeuritis multiplex, and nasal ulcers. Nonscarring alopecia is not typically associated with GPA.
